The workers also gaze at something more familiar : two monitors displaying The Weather Channel. Those in the control room are employees of a quasi-governmental entity called ERCOT, the Electrical Reliability Council of Texas. ERCOT's job is to make sure the power doesn't go out in Texas. As the first hot days of Texas summer count down to the scorching temperatures of late July and August, ERCOT managers say the grid is prepared. Most Texans knew little of the grid until August 2003, when the nation's largest power outage caused blackouts in the Northeast. 